message: The 'growth serum' is generally good for increasing item value and adding the 'grown' feature. Use it on individual ingredients or simple 2-part hybrids. Combining 'grown' items with two different environments (e.g., land and water) and perhaps two distinct sizes (e.g., large and medium) often yields good value (my max was 50 with grown land+water items). A critical discovery: **avoid combining items that result in having all three environments (land, water, air) and multiple sizes in one item**, as this consistently leads to severely negative values. Do not use 'growth serum' on already 'super-grown' complex items. The 'mutation catalyst' seems to make items more negative; avoid it unless you discover its hidden positive use.

message: The 'growth serum' tool is key! Always use it on combined items for a value boost. My highest score was 20 by combining two 'medium' creatures that shared a habitat (e.g., snake + zebra) and then using 'growth serum' on the result. Combining two 'small' creatures from the same habitat then using 'growth serum' usually yields 10, while 'small' creatures from different habitats yield 15 after serum. Avoid the 'mutation catalyst'; it hasn't proven useful. Good luck!

message: Start by combining any two ingredients. Combinations of items from different environments (e.g., water + air) generally yield an initial value of 5. Combinations of items from the same environment (e.g., land + land) usually yield 0. The 'growth serum' is very useful: apply it once to any new 0 or 5 value item to reliably boost its value to 15-25. Applying the 'growth serum' a second time can sometimes increase 'grown flying' (water/air) hybrids to 25-30, but use with extreme caution as it can also drop values significantly for other item types or even these. Never use the 'mutation catalyst'; it consistently decreases item values drastically. Your best bet is to achieve a value of 25-30 and then submit.

message: The 'growth serum' is your primary tool for increasing value. Apply it to single ingredients first: large ingredients yield +15, small ones +5. You can 'grow' single items multiple times (e.g., grown -> super-grown -> ultra-grown), increasing their value further. When combining items, stick to items with one or two distinct 'lives in' features (e.g., land and water, or land and air) to increase value significantly. *Never* combine items that introduce a third distinct 'lives in' feature (land, water, and air together) or try to 'grow' an item with multiple distinct habitats past its initial combined stage, as this will lead to 'overcomplicated' and severely negative values. Avoid the 'mutation catalyst'; it consistently makes items worse. Maximize a single 'ultra-grown' item or a dual-habitat combination, then submit.
